  pages =	 {54-57},
  month =	 {May},
  abstract =	 {Ken Raschke, manufacturing manager for AT&T's North Carolina Works (Winston-Salem, North Carolina), and several other managers devised a plan for the plant's closure. Specific efforts at AT&T included: 1. announcing the closure 11 months before layoffs began, 2. offering jobs at other AT&T plants to all hourly employees with over 15 years of service, 3. offering early retirement to all employees with at least 30 years of service, 4. offering free job training, and 5. offering free counseling. As part of the plan, AT&T and the Communications Workers of America (CWA) formed a partnership called "the alliance" that operated in concert with the state of North Carolina. In addition, the US Department of Labor gave the state a \$1.3-million grant to administer dislocated worker services at AT&T. However, some problems did arise. The plant closed earlier than AT&T's announced date, and employees did not feel that the closure was justified. Because AT&T addressed employee needs, no production, quality, or service problems were experienced during the closure months.}
