  abstract =	 {Recent research on the effect of advance notice on jobless duration following displacement misspecify the relationship between these 2 variables by treating advance notice as a dummy regressor in conventional survival time models. Job search theory, however, indicates that the major impact of advance notice is not to alter the efficiency of search after job loss, but rather to allow workers to begin a search before job loss. A "sequential-regimes" job search model is developed that allows searches prior to displacement for workers with advance knowledge of layoff, with different search intensities before and after layoff. Maximum-likelihood estimates of the model are computed using a pooled data set from the 1984 and 1986 Displaced Worker Surveys. Advance knowledge is found to significantly shorten jobless duration and may even benefit most labor force groups. }
